This paper is primarily focused on the development of algorithms for highly automated vehicles, which falls under the category of robotics (cs.RO). However, it also considers the behavior of human drivers and how it can be incorporated into these algorithms, which could be relevant to the sub-category of human-computer interaction (cs.HC). Additionally, the use of naturalistic driving data and the development of behavior models could involve machine learning and artificial intelligence (cs.AI), as well as control systems (cs.SY) and possibly even data analysis and statistics (cs.LG).
